{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b768ce72-fad5-4d9d-a5df-5cf3a43bc98c","content":"## x86-64 Microarchitecture Baseline Increase\n\n**.NET 9** raised the x86-64 baseline from **v1 → v2**, requiring SSE4.1, SSE4.2, SSSE3, and POPCNT. Your 2012-era hardware (likely Sandy Bridge/Ivy Bridge) supports v2, so .NET 10 worked fine.\n\n**.NET 11** most likely raised the baseline to **x86-64-v3**, which additionally requires **AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA, and F16C**. AVX2 debuted with **Haswell (2013)** — so your pre-2013 nodes fail at startup.\n\n**Why the other targets are unaffected:**\n- **Windows ARM64 (SQ1):** ARM — x86-64 levels don't apply\n- **Raspberry Pi 4:** ARM64 (Cortex-A72) — same, not affected\n\n**Your options:**\n1. **Retire the pre-Haswell nodes** — simplest long-term fix\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for workloads that must run on old hardware\n3. Check if the runtime offers a **compat switch or v2-baseline build** (historically not supported — the baseline is a hard requirement baked into the JIT and runtime libraries)\n\nYou can verify a node's support by running:\n\n```bash\n# Check for AVX2 support\ngrep -o 'avx2' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1\n```\n\nIf that returns nothing, the CPU is below v3 and can't run a v3-baseline .NET runtime.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d0b22e7-427f-4068-bc99-bda87dbc5def","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements.\n\nLet me explain what's happening:\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, the key change here is about .NET 10 vs .NET 11.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\n.NET 9 (released November 2024) did raise the x86-64 baseline to require x86-64-v2 instruction sets. For .NET 10 and .NET 11, these are future releases beyond my knowledge cutoff, so I need to be careful about what I claim regarding their specific requirements.\n\nThere's been discussion about potentially raising the baseline further to x86-64-v3 in future versions, which would add AVX, AVX2, and other instruction sets that came with Haswell in 2013. Most 2012 hardware should support x86-64-v2 since SSE4.2 was introduced with Nehalem in 2008, but x86-64-v3 support would be less certain for that era of processors. 3 in the future, which would require AVX2 support. Since the user's hardware is from 2012 (Sandy Bridge/Ivy Bridge era), it wouldn't have AVX2, explaining why the upgrade to .NET 11 breaks on those nodes. The error message they're seeing is exactly what .NET throws when the CPU lacks required baseline instruction sets. AVX2 was introduced in Haswell in 2013, so that's the cutoff for x86-64-v3 support. Let me provide a straightforward answer about what's happening here.","outputTokens":1535,"requestId":"B414:180EFF:8CBFD4:AE7349:6A01355E"},"id":"e33b19cf-44b8-4830-854c-6dbf16071d3c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:48:46.614Z","parentId":"f2f54a36-6ab4-4ad1-bc8b-39840cd0251f"}
